item.title: The minifigures have landed! Major props to @ironhaus_jimmy for the sculpt and @ericnilla for the molding and casting. These guys are two of our favorite artists working in the minifigure arena today, so it was an absolute honor to have them involved with this. Each minifigure pack with come with one figure (red, orange, or white), a sticker, and a card with a download code for the album. The header card is printed with elements of Caiden's artwork and hand stamped with our logo. This was a ton of fun to put together, so hopefully it'll be a cool way to extend the record experience into a more tactile/tangible dimension. These will be available next Tuesday when the album releases on our Bandcamp page. . . . . . #theminifiguremilitia #minifigures #minifigs #ericnilla #jimmyrommel #horace #godisthewarmestplacetohide #qoheleth

item.title: About
item.dc:creator: jehuthehunt@gmail.com
item.content:encoded:
QOHELETH is comprised of Jeremy Hunt, Mike Strickler, and Caiden Withey. The resulting sounds of this collective are rooted in discordance: loud, obnoxious, and discomforting. Across their first three releases, this trio has focused on these central tenets: pushing the boundaries of songwriting and noise to its limits, never standing in one place for long, and doing exactly what they want.

Through their music, they are attempting to collect and assemble the experiences of a fractured world into new expressions. As Flannery O’Connor once said, “You shall know the truth and the truth shall make you odd.”

Their first release, God is the Warmest Place to Hide (2017), took inspiration from the tagline of John Carpenter’s The Thing: “Man is the warmest place to hide.” As Carpenter’s film explored the uncertainty of what it means to be a human overtaken by unknown forces, this record asks what happens to us when we use the uncertainty of our perceptions and understandings of God as the justification for our darker actions. Their second record, Black Kite Broadcasts (2018), was released on Bad Cake Records, and tells the story of an intercepted radio signal from the future. Told through DJ vignettes and songs captured from bands that don't exist yet, it hits at an event sometime in the near future where humanity in the U.S. suffers an uprising at the hands of both animal and plant life. Album number three, Ape Dog Wars Chide the Stem Toil was issued at the end of 2018, on Philip K. Discs. It's the world's very first noise rock remix record, a complete reimagining of the debut album. It was deconstructed and remixed by their friend and collaborator, Whettman Chelmets. From top to bottom, it presents a new listening experience, illuminating electronic and industrial undertones within the original compositions.

These guys are two of our favorite artists working in the minifigure arena today, so it was an absolute honor to have them involved with this. Each minifigure pack with come with one figure (red, orange, or white), a sticker, and a card with a download code for the album. The header card is printed with elements of Caiden's artwork and hand stamped with our logo. This was a ton of fun to put together, so hopefully it'll be a cool way to extend the record experience into a more tactile/tangible dimension. item.title: Remembering Kurt
item.dc:creator: jehuthehunt@gmail.com
item.content:encoded:
In light of the anniversary of Kurt Cobain's death, here's a little story about the creation of one of our songs on Black Kite Broadcasts. Early on in the writing process, Mike & I were sending lots of ideas back and forth to each other, just whatever caught our ears and sparked ideas. Now Mike's mainly a drummer (and a killer one at that), but he also plays guitar and has a great ear for these fantastic hooks. So around Christmas 2017, he starts sending me all these little riffs and grooves that he's been writing.

One of them is labeled "Nirvana Song."

Obviously it wasn't meant to be a permanent title, but given our mutual love of the band, it immediately clicked when I first heard it. I instantly understood what he was going for with the vibe of the thing. Now at this point, I was mulling over concepts for a completely different album. I had it all mapped out in my head, I just hadn't started writing it yet.

But as soon as I heard Mike's "Nirvana Song," I knew we had to switch gears. What if this song was from a sort of Nirvana tribute band? One deeply influenced and inspired by them? Along with the other early ideas that we shared with each other, the concept of Black Kite started taking shape: bands from the future, riffing in a post-apocalyptic world.

And so that's how "Nirvana Song" became "Uterine" and one of our first fictional bands, Territorial Pissants, came into being. Obviously we'll never touch Nirvana's greatness or the heart and humor that Kurt brought to the world, but this was our small attempt at honoring him and his legacy. We miss you dude. Hope that you're at peace.

item.title: On Franklin Graham and toxic legacy…
item.dc:creator: jehuthehunt@gmail.com
item.content:encoded:
by Jeremy Hunt

Over the past few years during 45’s presidency, I’ve routinely watched Franklin Graham embrace a man who operates out of a place of fear, bullying, demeaning language and behavior, one who lies as easily as breathing…and it’s given me repeated pause to wonder what’s happening within the heart of a faith that I thought I once knew.

This is not to suggest that Graham is the only arbiter of what conservative, white Christianity in the U.S. does and thinks, but he is, in many ways, a sort of last bastion, a holdover from a period where his father was “America’s Pastor.” If you’ve been confused about how this slice of Christendom could embrace 45’s ascendency to power, I think Graham is a case study in the contradictions and shifting priorities in this union of religious and political power. 

You see, there was a time in my early working career where I was hired by the Billy Graham Evangelistic Association…and ended up staying there for six years (2006 - 2012). Like a lot of Christians, I had a ton of respect for Billy Graham and even though he wasn’t active on a daily basis with the ministry, the impression I got was that it was still following in his footsteps of sharing the love of Jesus and welcoming people into his presence. 

What I didn’t realize until it was too late was just how drastically Franklin was shifting the focus and weight of the ministry. The biggest example of this was the full embrace of partisan politics. While Billy was always close to U.S. Presidents, he managed to remain mostly above the fray and avoided outright endorsement of candidates and hot button issues. I don’t doubt that he had his own convictions and likely shared them with those closest to him, but externally, he steered clear of such things. For whatever reason, Franklin dove straight in. 

The Franklin of the BGEA was often combative, reductionist in his theology, narrow-minded in scope, and quick to embrace politics as a way of backing up the claims of that outlook on the world. Here are some of the things I experienced during my time there…

2007 - Ruth’s final resting place 

When Ruth Graham, everyone in the organization knew of her deep love and affinity for the North Carolina mountains that she and Billy had shared for years. While their presence was certainly felt in the Charlotte area, we all knew that the mountains were home.  And so when she died, we assumed that that’s where she would be buried. Until it wasn’t. Franklin had other ideas. The newly opened Billy Graham Library was positioned as a spinoff of presidential libraries, but in truth it was more of a museum, complete with a talking cow animatronic that greets visitors when they enter. It’s clear that no expense was spared in making it, but it was/is little more than an ode to Billy’s life in Disney-lite form. 

When Ruth died, Franklin saw an opportunity to give more weight to the property by burying her there (with the intent that Billy would be buried by her side when he passed). In essence, the son usurped the feelings and wishes of his mother in order to make this spot a more attractive pilgrimage spot for tourists. This was such a big deal that the Washington Post covered it here.For many of the long-time employees, folks that had made the move with the ministry from its initial headquarters in Minnesota down to North Carolina, this move by Franklin was extremely disconcerting. But it also made it clear that he was calling the shots and was fully capable of overpowering the wishes of his parents.

2008 - Casting Crowns tattoo

The image has since been removed (likely due to site updates and whatnot), but when this story originally ran, the web team was taken to task because the header photo we used of the band allowed some of their tattoos to be visible. Now if you don’t know anything about Casting Crowns, they’re one of the squeakiest clean bands in all of Contemporary Christian Music. They’re about as safe and inoffensive as you can get. Yet this photo right up there? It was too much for leadership to handle. A supporter might see that, view their presence on our site as an endorsement, and then decide to stop their donations.

Now this might seem like a relatively small thing, but this spoke volumes to how much clout the organization had over artists who wished to be welcomed into the fold. An endorsement and partnership from the BGEA could guarantee that a band would have paid performances at some of the biggest Christian events across the country and around the world. As we’re seeing folks like even David Crowder embrace the Franklin Graham stage, I think it’s important to remember just how tough it is for a band to make a living out of music in these days. I’m not justifying that decision by any means and each band will have to make their own peace with how they’ve partnered with Franklin, but the allure of a form of financial stability must be a strong one in order to appear at his events.

2008? - Point of Grace chest visibility

This fear-based approach to keeping up appearances informed this next example as well.  Similar to Casting Crowns, Point of Grace is one of CCM’s safest groups. Yet when we featured them in an interview on the BGEA website using a promo shot similar to this one, we were criticized for allowing such a large amount of skin from the chest area to be shown. We had to reach back out to their publicist for “better” options in order to avoid any “appearance of sin” or possible stumbling blocks for our readers (donors).

2008 - Jeremy Camp’s earrings / The Almost’s “demon eyes”

While at the BGEA, I had the chance to watch several friends in action as they created music videos for some of CCM’s biggest names. These folks were/are incredibly talented, some of the best creatives I’ve ever witnessed. But their work was often balanced on the razor’s edge, due to the whims of Franklin and his inner circle (more on one of those individuals in just a minute). The two key instances of this are the Jeremy Camp video for his song “Let It Fade” and this video for The Almost’s track, “Monster Monster.” Both of these videos nearly were left on the cutting room floor, so to speak. Their offenses? Jeremy Camp had his earrings in for his video. Yep, that’s right. Earrings.

For The Almost, cat-eye contact lenses were used to give Aaron Gillespie a different look for his monster alter-ego. Even though the video concept had made its way through the rigorous approvals (another hallmark of my time there: red tape and micromanaging to prevent anything remotely dangerous or risky getting out to the public), when the video was finished, we were told that we couldn’t release it as planned and that The Almost would have to do it on their own. If you’ve ever wondered about the damage done by this form of legalism, look no further than any of the recent interviews with Gillespie’s main band, Underoath, to see what their journey through the Christian machine has done to their faith.

2011 - Rob Bell, the heretic?

Love Wins was a controversial read for some when it first came out, but in Franklin’s case, a number of us employees doubted whether he even it read it to begin with. Yet there he was on TV within days of the release, calling Bell a heretic. Now if you spend any time online, “reading the comments,” you already know that this isn’t new territory (either then or now) for Bell. But behavior is indicative of Franklin’s willingness to make snap judgments about deep theological issues. There is no room for nuance here, no space for doubt. While I’m no fan of Bill O’Reilly, it's telling how his questions in this interview cause Franklin to spin on a dime and dismiss legitimate inquiries about whether Holocaust victims are in hell.

2011 - Billy Graham in Quotes / Donna Lee Toney 

In 2011, a book of compiled quotes from Billy Graham was released. They were arranged by topic and theme, and included some of his most famous sayings from his years of ministry. Sounds like an inspirational and encouraging tome, right? Yes, for the most part it is. Indeed, I used it quite frequently when I was an employee at the BGEA for a source of uplifting messages to share with our social media audience.

There was just one crucial catch: the authors of the book are credited as follows: “Franklin Graham with Donna Lee Toney. If that second name doesn’t ring a bell, here’s her official bio from the book published:

“Donna Lee Toney has been a colleague of Franklin Graham for over thirty years. Serving Samaritan’s Purse and the Billy Graham Evangelistic Association in many various capacities, she has also served in literary collaboration with the Grahams since 1982, including the most recent Billy Graham release Nearing Home andThe Sower with Franklin Graham.” 

That inner circle I mentioned earlier? Donna Toney was at the center of it. She had (possibly still has) Franklin’s ear in a way that few other people in the organization did. If you were working on a project that had to make it through the strenuous approvals process, you prayed that she wasn’t one of the people who would lay eyes on it. Those artist fiascos? Those were based largely on the fear that she or Franklin would disapprove and shut it all down.

Back to the book: because of her involvement, we actually had to check every time we used a quote with the citations in the back to make sure that the quote was sourced from a book that Billy wrote on his own, without her or Franklin. Why? This “saying” right here:

“[Christians] are called to distinguish themselves as Christ followers, not community organizers.” (p. 141)

Something about that one seemed off to us as employees and if it feels off to you, I’d suggest that it might have something to do with the terminology “community organizers.” While that concept isn’t new, it gained notoriety in the late 2000s/early 2010s thanks to Barack Obama’s work in community. Strangely enough, the book that this quote was pulled from (Storm Warning) was reissued in 2010 (a year after Obama was elected). And if you look at the notes about the changes to the new edition, you’ll see this thank you from Billy: 

“I am especially grateful, however, to Donna Lee Toney, who gave invaluable editorial and research assistance to this second edition and coordinated its final editing and publication. Without her dedication and literary skill, this project would never have been brought to completion.”

Now I could be mistaken about my take on this, but I would be shocked if Billy actually said that quote about community organizers. This is a man who got burned early in his career (and later in private conversations made public with Richard Nixon) due to politics. He may have had some concerns about President Obama, but passive aggressively calling out his career field in a quote like this feels quite petty and out of character. To that end, the internal consensus amongst employees was that this was yet another instance of Donna and Franklin making their presence known by jumping on the coat tails of Billy’s legacy.

2012 - NC Prop 1

Lastly, as I was in the process of leaving the organization in 2012, one of the final straws for me was a full page ad that Billy ostensibly took out in the Charlotte Observer in support of NC Proposition 1. You can read all about the situation here, but in essence, this was a declaration that only heterosexual marriage would be recognized by the state of North Carolina. Never mind the fact that there were already laws on the books asserting as much. This was yet another opportunity to make sure that the LGBTQ+ community in NC would know that they were secondary citizens.


As stated earlier, Billy’s unwillingness to dive into these sorts of political campaigns took a sudden about-face and he supposedly issued a statement in support of Prop 1 via an ad that was paid for with BGEA funds (i.e., donations from supporters). Again, many of us employees at the time suspected that it was Franklin moving the pen, not Billy (who was in his early 90s at this point). This wasn’t the first time that Franklin was accused of speaking for his father in the declining years of his life, and it wouldn't be the last. 

So why talk about all of this now? It’s not to try to convince Franklin to change or to bring about any sort of conviction in his heart. At 66, he is a man set in his ways and even though it’s been seven years since I left the BGEA, I’ve yet to see any news report or story about him that remotely contradicted the character impressions I got of him while working there or that demonstrate any semblance of growth or softening. 

And it’s not to try to convince any of his diehard supporters. I doubt that there’s much that could shift their opinion of him at this point.

No, I share these things because, if there’s any hope for a shift moving forward, I would hope that it would be other people who are possibly on the fence about supporting and listening to Franklin, simply because of who’s son he is. Billy has a legacy…and it’s one that Franklin has turned toxic. For the folks who read this who consider themselves evangelical Christians, he doesn’t deserve your support, your listening ear, or your time. He has embraced proximity to power, eschews humility and doubt, and cruises on complete certitude about the rightness of his narrow interpretation and application of Scripture. 

And he offers a veneer of spiritual respectability to a lying, manipulative, sexual predator of a president who wouldn’t know Jesus if he walked up to him and overturned his fast food-covered dinner tables and drove him, whip in hand, out of the White House.

item.title: Black and White Electric Light
item.dc:creator: jehuthehunt@gmail.com
item.content:encoded:
If you've been following us for any period of time, hopefully one of the themes that's come through the loudest in our music and creative impulses is our collective drive to experiment. Whether it's in our sonic presence, our visual art, or the continual digital dumpster diving we do for most of our videos, we are constantly trying to push our personal capabilities.

With that in mind, we're incredibly excited to share the newest iteration of that theme, "Black and White Electric Light." This is a short film that a friend of ours, director Mike Fink, recently completed. He reached out to us at the beginning of the project to see if we'd be interested in writing some music for the film and we leapt at the opportunity. All three of us love movies (as we explored just a bit last year with Alternative Control), and we had talked in the past about how much we would love to get a chance to score something in the future.

Thanks to Mike Fink, that future was here and now...and we had a blast with what he created. The film itself is about four minutes long, but in order to give him plenty to pick and choose from, we wrote about 20 minutes of original instrumental themes for this short. We knew going in that he wouldn't need all of it, but we wanted to give him plenty of mood pieces to incorporate as he saw fit. From a musical standpoint, we decided to take a minimalist approach to the instruments we used on each track. Several of them feature only bass and drums, with a hint of feedback or static here and there. One track was built only from a Casio mini-keyboard from our childhood, while another features only vocals and static. On the whole, it's a very different sound from what we've done before, which made it all the more exciting to try.

The end result is up there at the top of the post for you to see (and hear). We're thrilled with the results and we hope you dig it too. If you like it, please pass it along to others who might enjoy it. Thanks for watching.

item.title: Mark It Well...
item.dc:creator: jehuthehunt@gmail.com
item.content:encoded:
Music is a time machine. 

It elongates the minutes, shortens the days. 

Grace note years, whole note hours.

Music seeps into our brains and unmoors us from our temporal trappings and allows for visitations from the past, glimpses of unwritten futures…maybe even slightly frozen moments of the present, if we’re lucky.

These two pieces found themselves across a span of over a decade. Mike wrote and recorded track one in the mid-2000s, before either of us had any inkling that this band would exist one day. We were friends and played music together at that point, but the fires and frustrations that led us to this point were still being stoked and nurtured.

Meanwhile, this past summer, I improvised and recorded track two one afternoon while messing around with some keys. After listening back, I wasn’t sure where the piece belonged, so I set it aside for the time being.

Fast-forward a few weeks and I was organizing some files and decided that it needed a name, if only so I could find it at some point later on. Thinking of the poetic way that Stephen King names the transition from life to death in The Dark Tower series, it was entitled “The Clearing at the End is the Path.” In the turning of the wheel in Mid-World, this phrase (or one close to it) offers up the visual of one walking out of the forest of life, into the open space and peace of whatever comes next. My brain jumped back to Mike’s “These Exquisitely Dressed Trees,” based simply on the imagery of his title. I played them back to back and the hairs on my skin stood up. 

A quick conversation back and forth and he shared the same experience. Mysteriously, through the years, these were meant for each other. And somehow, they were/are/will be reflections on the life that we’re all lucky to have and the death that will one day come for all of us.

Staccato dreams, legato fears.

Time has music in its gears.
